Event Name: Burien Wastemobile
Event description/details:
The Wastemobile travels to many communities to provide household hazardous waste disposal services for King County residents and accepts a wide variety of materials.

Business waste is accepted from conditionally exempt small quantity generators (SQGs). For more details and to find out if you qualify as an SQG, contact the business waste line at 206-263-8899 or see the website for more details.

Restrictions: No latex paint accepted. There is a limit of 50 gallons for most liquid hazardous waste per residential customer per day at all Wastemobile events. 25 gallon limit on gasoline, oil and antifreeze. No containers over five gallons in size will be accepted.

Amounts and types of business waste are restricted. See the website for complete details.

Proper handling and transportation of hazardous waste can reduce the chance of accidental spills. For your safety and the safety of the Hazardous Waste Program staff, please:

  • Don't mix products.
  • Keep products in original containers.
  • Label products not in original containers.
  • Secure products so they won't tip over and/or leak.
  • Store products away from the passenger compartment of your vehicle and keep them separate from items you wish to keep.
  • Stay in your vehicle during unloading.

Event Name: COVID-19 Vaccination Pop-up at Holy Temple Evangelistic Center
Event description/details:
When: Saturday, November 13, 2:00 PM - 5:30 PM

Where: Holy Temple Evangelistic Center - 12600 Renton Ave S, Seattle 98178

Vaccine Available(s): Pfizer, Moderna, Johnson & Johnson

Partner(s): Cierra Sisters

Please Note:

Walk-ups welcome. No appointment needed.

Vaccine(s) are FREE to everyone age 12 and up, regardless of your income, insurance, citizenship, or immigration status.

Children, Ages 12-17 can get Pfizer ONLY and must be accompanied by a parent or legal guardian.

Vaccine shots & recovery time take approximately 20 minutes.

Free rides to and from events and appointments are available. Call 425-943-6706 or go to, bit.ly/vaxride.

If you have a disability and need reasonable ADA accommodation(s) available by request. Call 206.477.3977, 8am to 7pm (interpreters available) or email publichealthaccommodations@kingcounty.gov.

For language interpretation, call 206.477.3977, 8am to 7pm. (Say your preferred language in English when connected).

* Drop-in COVID-19 booster shots are available for eligible adults, age 18 and up, at all of our King County vaccination sites (no appointment needed). For a list of sites, go to: kingcounty.gov/vaccine. For more information about booster eligibility, go to: bit.ly/CDC-VaxBoosters

* A third dose of the Pfizer or Moderna COVID-19 vaccine is only for people with significantly compromised immune systems. The new recommendation does not apply to people who got the J&J vaccine. For more info, go to bit.ly/third-dose.

Event Name: Leave Administration 101
Event description/details:
Audience: HR professionals/leave administrators

Please join the Leave Administration Team for our 2-hour Leave Administration 101 class which will provide the basics of leave administration. This class includes a leave overview, roles/responsibilities, and a review of leave forms/materials

You will learn: 

• Leave administration process flow

• Understanding leave basics (types of leave)

• Know your role (roles and responsibilities)

• Leave administration resources and tips (forms, guides, resources)

• Centralized leave experts to provide King County standard answers

If you are interested in signing up for reoccurring leave administration classes then please send an email to KC.leaveadmin@kingcounty.gov. Classes are available using Skype or by phone (206-263-8114, ID# 203683).
Host/Contact Department: King County Benefits, Payroll and Retirement Operations

Event Name: Disaster Reporting Open House
Event description/details:
King County residents and business owners who have questions about reporting property damage or other losses from the recent storms and flooding, or need help completing a report, are invited to an open house this week.

The event will take place on Thursday, February 13 from 6:30 to 8:30 p.m. at Lord of Life Lutheran Church and Community Center, 12819 160th Ave. SE in Renton. Staff from King County Emergency Management, the Department of Local Services, and other King County agencies will be on hand to talk to residents and business owners, answer questions about the disaster assistance process, and provide help in filling out the damage assessment form. Light refreshments will be provided. 

King County Emergency Management is currently collecting information regarding weather-related damage and losses suffered since January 20. If your home or business sustained damage as a result of the severe weather, you may be eligible for federal disaster assistance. Eligibility is determined through an assessment process that takes into account the total reported losses within King County. Submitting a report does not guarantee reimbursement. 

Damage reporting forms are available online at kingcounty.gov/damage. Reports can also be filed by calling 1-800-523-5044 from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. weekdays excluding holidays. Reports must be filed by February 21. 

For more information about the open house, email AskLocalServices@kingcounty.gov or call 1-800-523-5044.

Event Name: Disaster Preparedness Workshop
Event description/details:
King County is prone to many hazards, and when one happens many services we rely on will be overwhelmed. It may be difficult for residents to travel or communicate. Residents need to be prepared to be self-sufficient during these times. Understanding of disaster skills is critical to being prepared.

This workshop will provide an overview on hazards and the certain skills needed after a disaster. We will cover topics related to: local hazards, utility control, water storage/purification, emergency sanitation, creating emergency plans and ways to make it through events that might disrupt your normal daily routine.

Event Name: Progress Notes training
Event description/details: This training is part of the King County Behavioral Health and Recovery Division (BHRD) Onboarding Academy series for behavioral health clinical staff working within the King County Provider Network. This training covers clinical reasons for writing progress notes, why interventions are a required component of clinical documentation, progress note pitfalls, tools to write stronger –not longer –progress notes and incorporating the Golden Thread. Upon completion, participants are eligible to receive 1.5 NASW/NAADAC continuing education credit.

Event Name: Charter Review Commission Community Meeting
Event description/details:
The King County Charter provides the basic long-term structure for King County government. The charter institutionalizes core values of checks and balances, accountability, and merit, and seeks to promote an effective, efficient, and responsive government. Every ten years, King County is required to review the charter. The Charter Review Commission leads this work and makes recommendations for amendments that are then presented to voters.

In order to guide this work, the CRC is conducting community outreach to collect input on how the charter might be improved or changed, which in turn could help make King County government more responsive and effective.

Please join us at one of our upcoming community meetings to share feedback on potential amendments to the King County Charter. Your feedback is important to this work. You may also submit your feedback via email at CharterReview@kingcounty.gov.

Event Name: Damarius Butts Inquest Hearing
Elevate Recovery Advocacy Trainings
Event description/details:
Elevate Recovery Advocacy is the Washington Recovery Alliance’s signature public policy and media engagement program. It is more than a training—it is the foundation of a statewide recovery movement. In the past two years, the WRA has trained over 500 Washingtonians who’ve been impacted by mental health and substance use challenges.

Elevate trainings provide tangible skills, such as:

– How to tell your (or a loved one or client’s) story in a way that is succinct and compelling

– Understanding the legislative process at different levels of government

– How to persuade a policymaker

– How to work with the media

– How to get involved in the recovery movement

Upcoming trainings will be posted on this page, sent to our email listserv, and posted on our Facebook page.

2020 Summer Elevate Trainings:

August 8th or September 12th

Event Name: Lower Green River Flood Management Plan Public Meeting
Event description/details: The King County Flood Control District is preparing a Lower Green River Corridor Flood Hazard Management Plan for approximately 21 river miles of the Lower Green River that flow through the cities of Auburn, Kent, Renton, Tukwila, and unincorporated King County. The goal of the Plan is to provide a long-term approach to reduce flood risk and improve fish habitat while supporting the economic prosperity of the region. A public scoping meeting will be held in January to share information with members of the public and solicit feedback on the plan.?

Event Name: Movies at Marymoor: Ferris Bueller's Day Off
Event description/details:
Join King County Parks this summer for the BECU Movies@Marymoor outdoor cinema series. Events are dog friendly and include live entertainment, food trucks, and big screen movies under the stars.

Seating opens at 6:30 p.m. Movies start at dusk. Admission is $5 cash per person or $6 credit. Kids under ages 5 and under are free.

Outside food and beverage is allowed.

For more information, visit moviesatmarymoor.com or facebook.com/moviesatmarymoor. The series is produced by Epic Events and presented by Overlake Medical Clinics.

Seating is on the grass; low-back chairs or blankets are recommended.

A $5 parking permit is required to park at Marymoor, which can be purchased from the vending machines located throughout the park.

This is a dog-friendly event. Pets must remain on a leash at all times.

There are no ATMs on site.

Event Name: COVID-19 Vaccination Pop-up at Washington Elementary
Event description/details:
The Alliance of People with disAbilities, in partnership with Public Health Seattle King County, the Seattle Cancer Care Alliance, and the Auburn School District is hosting a fully accessible and inclusive vaccination clinic for youth with disabilities (12+).

When: Saturday, June 5 10AM-1PM

Where: Washington Elementary, 20 E St NE, Auburn WA

Who: This event has been specifically tailored and designed for:

  • People with disabilities (12+)
  • Family members of people with disabilities
  • Caregivers

Translation Services: ASL & Deaf-Blind Interpreters are available to be on-site if there is a need. Please indicate if you have this need in your registration.

Accommodations/Other Services: In-car vaccinations are available for people who have difficulty ambulating, easy access to seating in all areas of the clinic, low-sensory clinic, fidget/sensory items available, space to pace/walk, volunteers trained in the communication/behavioral needs of people with disabilities. Spoken language interpreters available upon request.

This clinic will be distributing first dose vaccinations of Pfizer. Parental consent is required for vaccination of a minor. Second dose appointments will be scheduled at the clinic for June 26.

QUESTIONS? Please contact kayla@disabilitypride.org

Event Name: Leave Administration for Supervisors
Event description/details:
Audience: King County supervisors

Please join the Leave Administration Team for an overview of King County leave programs. This online training is intended for supervisors to learn more about King County employee leave programs and policies, and the supervisor’s role and responsibility regarding leave administration. Special attention will be paid to FMLA/KCFML policies.

You will learn:

• How to identify an employee’s potential need for leave

• When and what to say

• What not to say or ask

• Your role as a supervisor in leave administration

Event Name: World Premiere of "Spawning Grounds"
Event description/details:
Spawning Grounds is a documentary film about the kokanee in Lake Sammamish. The world premiere showing will be at the North Bend Theatre on Saturday, January 18. Doors open at 6:00pm and the film will start at 7:30pm.

These fish play an important role in our region, but the number of fish that survive to return and spawn has been very low in recent years.  

Tickets are $20 if purchased in advance online or $25 at the door.  

Support for Spawning Grounds comes from King County, 4Culture, Snoqualmie Tribe, the cities of Issaquah and Sammamish, and many other organizations.
Location:
125 Bendigo Blvd N
North Bend, WA 98041
(47.495879, -121.78648)

Event Name: Voter registration deadline
National Night Out
Event description/details: National Night Out is an annual community-building campaign that promotes partnerships between law enforcement, first responders, and other government agencies and the people they all serve. The purpose of NNO is to make our neighborhoods safer, more caring places to live. This annual event, held the first Tuesday in August, enhances the relationship between neighbors and law enforcement while bringing back a true sense of community. It also provides a great opportunity to bring police and neighbors together under positive circumstances. To celebrate NNO, many neighborhoods host block parties, festivals, parades, cookouts and various other community events with safety demonstrations, seminars, youth events, visits from emergency personnel, exhibits and much, much more. National Night Out is sponsored by the National Association of Town Watch (NATW).

Event Name: Local voters' pamphlets mailed
Free Disaster Skills Workshop
Event description/details:
King County is prone to many hazards, and when one happens many services we rely on will be overwhelmed. It may be difficult for residents to travel or communicate. Residents need to be prepared to be self-sufficient during these times. Understanding of disaster skills is critical to being prepared.

Our free workshop will provide an overview on hazards and certain skills needed after a disaster. We will cover topics related to local hazards, utility control, water storage/purification, emergency sanitation, creating emergency plans, and ways to make it through events that might disrupt your normal daily routine. 

All participants are welcome. Registration is free, and required. You do not need to bring your ticket to the training. You can register at https://bit.ly/37hI6Qi 

For questions about accessibility, or to request an accommodation, please contact Sophia Lopez at slopez@kingcounty.gov or 206-205-6545. (Requests should be made at least 14 calendar days prior to the workshop.)

Event Name: Rev Up For Retirement!
Event description/details:
Are you too young to think about retirement? Think again!

This retirement overview is for anyone thinking about retiring in the next few years. With increasing concern over the future of Social Security and the stability of retirement plans, it?s a good idea to stay informed and prepare in advance.

Join us for a three-hour seminar where you?ll learn more about pensions, Medicare, Social Security, the current retirement climate, and projections for the future. We?ll also share information about the resources available to you through King County.

Registration is required.

Please note: Attendance is strictly voluntary, on your own time, and non-work related.
Location name: King Street Center - 8th Floor Conference Room

Event Name: Case Management training
Event description/details: This training is part of the King County Behavioral Health and Recovery Division (BHRD) Onboarding Academy series for behavioral health clinical staff working within the King County Provider Network. This training will define case management, identify the activities and services it includes, and explain how to successfully and efficiently document case management in individual service plans (ISP) and progress notes. Upon completion, participants are eligible to receive 1.5 NASW/NAADAC continuing education credit.

Event Name: Trusted Partner Network Lunch & Learn
Event description/details: The Trusted Partner Network (TPN) is an effort to reach every person living in King County with critical lifesaving emergency alerts, regardless of whether they speak English. Trusted community members trained in the TPN will convey urgent public messages and necessary information regarding natural and man-made disasters or other emergencies to their community. The TPN aims to ensure more equitable outcomes after disasters.

Event Name: Rev Up for Retirement
Event description/details:
Are you too young to think about retirement? Think again!

This retirement overview is for anyone thinking about retiring in the next few years. With increasing concern over the future of Social Security and the stability of retirement plans, it?s a good idea to stay informed and prepare in advance.

Join us for a three-hour seminar where you?ll learn more about pensions, Medicare, Social Security, the current retirement climate, and projections for the future. We?ll also share information about the resources available to you through King County.

Registration is required.

Please note: Attendance is strictly voluntary, on your own time, and non-work related.

Event Name: Out of state ballots mailed for General election
Medical Necessity training
Event description/details: This training is part of the King County Behavioral Health and Recovery Division (BHRD) Onboarding Academy series for behavioral health clinical staff working within the King County Provider Network. This training will introduce the concept of medical necessity in behavioral health services and its role in maintaining a Golden Thread within an individual’s care. Participants also will learn how to establish and document medical necessity clearly in assessments, individual service plans and progress notes. Upon completion, participants are eligible to receive 1.5 NASW/NAADAC continuing education credit

Event Name: Deadline to submit flood damage reports
Event description/details:
Flooding, wind, and landslides from recent winter storms have buffeted residents and businesses across King County. Those who suffered property damage or other losses since January 20, 2020 may be eligible for financial assistance. Eligibility is determined through a damage assessment process, now underway, that takes into account the total reported losses within King County.

Individuals and businesses in King County are encouraged to submit reports of losses to King County Emergency Management online at kingcounty.gov/damage or by phone at 1-800-523-5044. Deadline to submit a report is February 21. 

Submitting a report does not guarantee reimbursement. 

Damage reports are for uninsured losses. Before filing a damage report with King County, residents and business owners should contact their insurance provider about existing coverage and deductibles. They are also urged to document damage with photographs and keep records of all cleanup and repair costs.

Event Name: Elevate Recovery Advocacy Training
Event description/details:
Elevate Recovery Advocacy is the Washington Recovery Alliance’s signature public policy and media engagement program. It is more than a training—it is the foundation of a statewide recovery movement. In the past two years, the WRA has trained over 500 Washingtonians who’ve been impacted by mental health and substance use challenges.

Elevate trainings provide tangible skills, such as:

– How to tell your (or a loved one or client’s) story in a way that is succinct and compelling

– Understanding the legislative process at different levels of government

– How to persuade a policymaker

– How to work with the media

– How to get involved in the recovery movement

Upcoming trainings will be posted on this page, sent to our email listserv, and posted on our Facebook page.

2020 Summer Elevate Trainings:

August 8th or September 12th

Event Name: World Premiere of "Spawning Grounds"
Event description/details:
Spawning Grounds is a documentary film about the kokanee in Lake Sammamish. The world premiere showing will be at the North Bend Theatre on Saturday, January 18. Doors open at 6:00pm and the film will start at 7:30pm.

These fish play an important role in our region, but the number of fish that survive to return and spawn has been very low in recent years.  

Tickets are $20 if purchased in advance online or $25 at the door.  

Support for Spawning Grounds comes from King County, 4Culture, Snoqualmie Tribe, the cities of Issaquah and Sammamish, and many other organizations.
Location:

Event Name: Intermittent Leave for FLSA-Exempt Employees
Event description/details:
Audience: HR and timekeeping professionals

Please join the Leave Administration Team to review and discuss a policy change that impacts how we will track intermittent leave for FLSA-exempt employees. This new policy will impact the leave administration process, agency standardization, and how applicable FMLA leave is tracked in the payroll system.?

Topics covered:?

  • An overview of the current policy
  • Intermittent leave under FMLA and FLSA
  • The new HR policy and how it will impact the FMLA process
  • Project timeline and deliverables
  • Who it impacts
  • Questions and answers

Join this hour-long training session by phone, over Skype, or in person (very limited capacity). A Skype invitation will be sent on the morning of the training for those that sign up. We will also present this information at the April PeopleSoft forum on April 3.

Event Name: Movies at Marymoor: The Sandlot
Event description/details:
Join King County Parks this summer for the BECU Movies@Marymoor outdoor cinema series. Events are dog friendly and include live entertainment, food trucks, and big screen movies under the stars.

Seating opens at 6:30 p.m. Movies start at dusk. Admission is $5 cash per person or $6 credit. Kids under ages 5 and under are free.

Outside food and beverage is allowed.

For more information, visit moviesatmarymoor.com or facebook.com/moviesatmarymoor. The series is produced by Epic Events and presented by Overlake Medical Clinics.

Seating is on the grass; low-back chairs or blankets are recommended.

A $5 parking permit is required to park at Marymoor, which can be purchased from the vending machines located throughout the park.

This is a dog-friendly event. Pets must remain on a leash at all times.

There are no ATMs on site.

Redmond, WA 98052

This is a dog-friendly event. Pets must remain on a leash at all times.

There are no ATMs on site.

Board for Developmental Disabilities Monthly Meeting
Event description/details: The Board for Developmental Disabilities is a 15-member citizen advisory board that provides oversight of community services for children with developmental delays, adults with developmental disabilities, and their families. The board develops plans for developmental disability services, advises on funding priorities, and advocates for increases in funding and improvements in services. Leave Administration 201
Event description/details:
Audience: HR professionals/leave administrators.

Please join the Leave Administration Team for a more in-depth look into the leave administration process. In this two-hour program, we?ll go beyond the basics and dive deeper into what it means to administer leave for King County employees. This training will provide more insight into the legal aspects of leave, key tips, and points to ponder.?

You will learn:

  • Complexities of administering multiple types of leave
  • Review actual case examples using detailed graphs
  • Tips and tricks of best leave practices
  • Legislative updates
  • Tools and resources to simplify leave administration

Participants may join by phone, over Skype, or attend in person. A Skype invitation will be sent out the morning of the training for those that signed up.

Join by Skype: 206-263-8114, ID# 203683

Event Name: Disaster Preparedness Workshop
Event description/details:
King County is prone to many hazards, and when one happens many services we rely on will be overwhelmed. It may be difficult for residents to travel or communicate. Residents need to be prepared to be self-sufficient during these times. Understanding of disaster skills is critical to being prepared.

This workshop will provide an overview on hazards and the certain skills needed after a disaster. We will cover topics related to: local hazards, utility control, water storage/purification, emergency sanitation, creating emergency plans and ways to make it through events that might disrupt your normal daily routine.

Event Name: Discovery Park Reservoir Open House
Event description/details:
Work this summer by the King County Wastewater Treatment Division (WTD) to modify an underground water reservoir in Seattle?s Discovery Park will require partial closures to portions of two hiking trails.

An open house on Feb. 23 at the Discovery Park Environmental Learning Center in Seattle will provide details of the work, which will take three to five months to complete and require partial closures along the Loop and Capehart trails.

The open house runs from 10 a.m. to noon at the learning center, 3801 Discovery Park Blvd.

King County is protecting public health with upgrades to the underground water-storage facility by providing safe and efficient access for annual inspections, and by meeting current standards for protecting water sources.

Event Name: Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Celebration
Event description/details:
Now in its 32nd year, King County will again celebrate the life and legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., our county's namesake. This annual celebration recognizes the impact that Dr. King had on our community and our nation, and reminds us to keep striving toward his dream of equity and justice.

This year's program will include music, spoken word, and a keynote by Ijeoma Oluo, local New York Times bestselling author of So You Want to Talk About Race.

As a part of the 2019 celebration, county officials are inviting the public to put into words or pictures the ideas and ideals for America and the world Dr. King gave his life for. The county is looking for the public's interpretation, a photo, a work of art, or an essay, of the theme for the 2019 celebration, which is taken from a quote by Dr. King: "I believe that unarmed truth and unconditional love will have the final word in reality. "

Please submit your work via email at esj@kingcounty.gov.

Open Enrollment
Event description/details:
Open Enrollment for next year's benefits takes place Nov. 1 � 15. Open Enrollment is your opportunity to:

  • Enroll in a Flexible Spending Account�Health Care and Dependent Day Care FSAs reduce your taxable income�saving you money. You must re-enroll every year during Open Enrollment. The Health Care FSA maximum contribution for 2020 is $2,700.
  • Select the appropriate Benefit Access Fee�or exemption. If you cover a spouse or domestic partner on your medical plan, a Benefit Access Fee may be automatically applied, depending on your benefit group and the plan you choose. If you qualify for an exemption, you must confirm this each year during Open Enrollment. If no action is taken during Open Enrollment and you later determine that you qualified for an exemption, fees already deducted will not be refunded.
  • Change medical plans�Use the Plan Comparison Charts and other resources on the Medical plans page to consider whether Kaiser SmartCare or KingCare Select (Regence) makes sense for your family. These plans will likely save you money, with lower deductibles, copays, and Benefit Access Fees. The KingCare (Regence) plan is also still available. Note: KingCare Select is not available to Deputy Sheriff/PSPMA and TEA-DOT employees.

Event Name: Community Planning Session: Remote Access from Rural Food Banks
Event description/details:
You are invited to a Veterans, Seniors and Human Services Levy (VSHSL) virtual Community Planning Session to inform the upcoming funding opportunity: Remote Access from Rural Food Banks Pilot.

This strategy seeks to improve access to services for individuals in rural areas through rural food banks that will operate as centralized points of access from which residents may increase knowledge about what human services may be available to meet their needs, connect to service providers and/or potentially receive direct support or assistance at this centralized location. The aim of this pilot is to increase access to information about service availability and increase access to services themselves in rural areas.

Please join us at an upcoming community planning session to inform this upcoming funding opportunity!

Charter Review Commission Community Meeting
Event description/details:
The King County Charter provides the basic long-term structure for King County government. The charter institutionalizes core values of checks and balances, accountability, and merit, and seeks to promote an effective, efficient, and responsive government. Every ten years, King County is required to review the charter. The Charter Review Commission leads this work and makes recommendations for amendments that are then presented to voters.

In order to guide this work, the CRC is conducting community outreach to collect input on how the charter might be improved or changed, which in turn could help make King County government more responsive and effective.

Please join us at one of our upcoming community meetings to share feedback on potential amendments to the King County Charter. Your feedback is important to this work. You may also submit your feedback via email at CharterReview@kingcounty.gov.

32627 SE Redmond-Fall City Rd
Fall City, WA 98024
(47.572391, -121.904325)

Event Name: Recovery Competencies for Behavioral Health Professionals training
Event description/details: Workforce training in recovery principles is one strategy King County’s Behavioral Health and Recovery Division implements to shift the publicly funded behavioral health system toward a recovery and resiliency orientation. This training is part of the King County Behavioral Health and Recovery Division (BHRD) Onboarding Academy series for behavioral health clinical staff working within the King County Provider Network. The training will introduce behavioral health professionals to the knowledge, skills, and practice behaviors needed to become competent in the delivery of recovery oriented behavioral health services. Core areas of knowledge and skills will be presented within seven performance domains: (1) interpersonal competencies, (2) professional role, (3) community integration, (4) assessment, planning and outcomes, (5) strategies for facilitating recovery, (6) system competencies, and (7) supporting holistic health. Upon completion, participants are eligible to receive 1.5 NASW/NAADAC continuing education credit.

Event Name: Bidder's Conference - Short-Term Engagement Projects for Seniors
Virtual Día de Los Muertos (Day 2)
Event description/details:
Day of the Dead (Día De Los Muertos) is a two day Mexican holiday (Nov. 1 & Nov. 2) for celebrating the lives of beloved family members. As portrayed in the Disney film, COCO, families create ofrendas (offerings) to honor their departed family members with bright colors, photos and sharing memories. This year, Sound Transit's LIT ERG invites you to celebrate the lives of your dearly departed family and friends by joining us Monday, Nov. 1 and Tuesday, Nov. 2, noon, for an hour to share our memories and learn more about Día De Los Muertos.

LIT invites you to visit Día de Los Muertos virtual altar and share thoughts, post a picture or offer a favorite food to honor the memory of a loved one.
Host/Contact Department: Sound Transit's Latinx in Transportation Employee Resource Group (LIT ERG)

Event Name: Trusted Partner Network Lunch & Learn
Event description/details: The Trusted Partner Network (TPN) is an effort to reach every person living in King County with critical lifesaving emergency alerts, regardless of whether they speak English. Trusted community members trained in the TPN will convey urgent public messages and necessary information regarding natural and man-made disasters or other emergencies to their community. The TPN aims to ensure more equitable outcomes after disasters.

Are you planning to retire in the next six months? If so, join your Retirement Team for this informative two-hour class. We’ll discuss procedures and forms, medical coverage options, and pension plans—so you’ll be on a smooth road toward a happy retirement.

Road to Retirement is offered in two locations—the Elections office in Renton and the Chinook Building in Seattle. Registration is required.

Event Name: Medical Necessity training
Event description/details: This training is part of the King County Behavioral Health and Recovery Division (BHRD) Onboarding Academy series for behavioral health clinical staff working within the King County Provider Network. This training will introduce the concept of medical necessity in behavioral health services and its role in maintaining a Golden Thread within an individual’s care. Participants also will learn how to establish and document medical necessity clearly in assessments, individual service plans and progress notes. Upon completion, participants are eligible to receive 1.5 NASW/NAADAC continuing education credit.

Event Name: Local voters' pamphlets mailed
Burien City Council Recovery Month Proclamation
Disaster Preparedness Workshop
Event description/details:
King County is prone to many hazards, and when one happens many services we rely on will be overwhelmed. It may be difficult for residents to travel or communicate. Residents need to be prepared to be self-sufficient during these times. Understanding of disaster skills is critical to being prepared.

This workshop will provide an overview on hazards and the certain skills needed after a disaster. We will cover topics related to: local hazards, utility control, water storage/purification, emergency sanitation, creating emergency plans and ways to make it through events that might disrupt your normal daily routine.
Location name: King County Library - White Center Branch

Event Name: Disaster Preparedness Workshop
Event description/details:
King County is prone to many hazards, and when one happens many services we rely on will be overwhelmed. It may be difficult for residents to travel or communicate. Residents need to be prepared to be self-sufficient during these times. Understanding of disaster skills is critical to being prepared.

This workshop will provide an overview on hazards and the certain skills needed after a disaster. We will cover topics related to: local hazards, utility control, water storage/purification, emergency sanitation, creating emergency plans and ways to make it through events that might disrupt your normal daily routine.

Event Name: What does LATINX Mean to You? Art Contest
Event description/details:
Eng:

Latinx/Hispanic Heritage Month! The King County Latinx Affinity Group (KCLx) is excited to kickoff a variety of events and discussions that celebrate the colorful and eclectic heritage of Latinx identity – but KCLx is curious, what does this identity mean to you?

To kickoff Heritage Month, KCLx is launching the “What does LATINX mean to you?” Art Contest! This contest event is your opportunity to showcase your unique interpretation of Latinx/o, Chicanx/o, and Hispanic identity; we all share common stories (culture, heritage, traditions, etc.) but how is your story read?

WHAT (QUE?): Submit any poem, video, or art piece (created by you) that answers the question: “What does being Latinx mean to you?”
Contest submissions accepted via email – diego.galvan@kingcounty.gov.
Art contest submissions will be placed on display in the virtual KCLx Art Gallery.

WHO (QUIEN?): The contest is open to any King County resident who self-identifies as Latinx, Chicanx, and/or Hispanic. (Feel free to share and spread the word!)

WHEN (CUANDO?): Submissions will be accepted from September 15th through October 8th. Voting will be conducted by the KCLx Leadership Committee from October 11th-15th. Winners will be announced October 15th.

WHY (POR QUE?): Acknowledging and respecting diversity within our common heritage is what allows the Latinx community to flourish and thrive… but also the top 3 winners, selected by the KCLx Leadership Committee, will win a gift card prize!
GRAND PRIZE - $75
2nd Place - $50
3rd Place - $25

We look forward to admiring your artistic interpretations of Latinx identity! If you have any questions or concerns, please feel free to contact us. 


Span:

¡Feliz Mes de la Herencia Latina/Hispana! El Grupo de Afinidad Latinx del Condado de King (KCLx) esta emocionado en iniciar una variedad de eventos y discursos que celebran la herencia colorida y ecléctica de la identidad Latina, pero KCLx tiene curiosidad, ¿qué significa esta identidad para usted?

Para dar inicio al Mes de la Herencia, KCLx lanza el concurso de arte "¿Qué significa LATINX para ti?" Este evento de concurso es su oportunidad de exhibir su interpretación única de la identidad latina, chicana o hispana; todos compartimos historias en común (cultura, herencia, tradiciones, etc.) pero ¿cómo se lee tu historia?

QUE (¿QUE?): Envíe cualquier poema, video u obra de arte (creada por usted) que responda a la pregunta: "¿Qué significa para usted ser Latinx/o/a?"
Las presentaciones del concurso de arte se exhibirán en la Galería de Arte virtual de KCLx. Las presentaciones del concurso se aceptan por correo electrónico: diego.galvan@kingcounty.gov

QUIEN (¿QUIEN?): El concurso está abierto a cualquier residente del condado de King que se identifique como latinx, chicanx y / o hispano.

CUANDO (¿CUÁNDO?): Las presentaciones del concurso de arte serán aceptadas desde el 15 de septiembre hasta el 8 de octubre. Los ganadores serán anunciados el 15 de octubre.

POR QUÉ (¿POR QUE?): Reconocer y respetar la diversidad dentro de nuestra herencia común es lo que permite que la comunidad Latinx prospere... ¡pero también los 3 ganadores principales, seleccionados por el Comité de Liderazgo de KCLx, ganarán un premio con una tarjeta de regalo!
GRAN PREMIO - $ 75
Segundo lugar - $ 50
Tercer lugar - $ 25

¡Esperamos poder admirar sus interpretaciones artísticas de la identidad Latinx! Si tiene alguna pregunta o inquietud, no dude en contactarnos.

Event Name: Virtual Día de Los Muertos (Day 1)
Event description/details:
Day of the Dead (Día De Los Muertos) is a two day Mexican holiday (Nov. 1 & Nov. 2) for celebrating the lives of beloved family members. As portrayed in the Disney film, COCO, families create ofrendas (offerings) to honor their departed family members with bright colors, photos and sharing memories. This year, Sound Transit's LIT ERG invites you to celebrate the lives of your dearly departed family and friends by joining us Monday, Nov. 1 and Tuesday, Nov. 2, noon, for an hour to share our memories and learn more about Día De Los Muertos.

LIT invites you to visit Día de Los Muertos virtual altar and share thoughts, post a picture or offer a favorite food to honor the memory of a loved one.
Host/Contact Department: Sound Transit's Latinx in Transportation Employee Resource Group (LIT ERG)

Event Name: Natural Yard Care Class
Event description/details:
Healthy soil is the foundation of a successful landscape. Learn from a soil scientist about the components of a robust soil system and how to make it work better for your landscape. The second half of class will be dedicated to teaching you how to make your soil even better by effectively using compost and mulch.

All participants that attend this class will receive discount coupons for the Snohomish Conservation District plant sale, and be able to scoop compost to take home!

Register at https://foundationofyouryard2019.eventbrite.com

Event Name: Community Planning Session: Caregiver Community Building and Caregiver Respite
Event description/details: You are invited to a Veterans, Seniors and Human Services Levy (VSHSL) virtual Community Planning Session to share plans and get input on an upcoming funding opportunity. This opportunity includes the investment for two strategies: Caregiver Community Building and Caregiver Respite. This opportunity seeks to support caregivers of seniors, age 55 and older, and caregivers of veterans and military servicemembers and their respective families, with meaningful community building and respite services. Guidance provided by the VSHSL Implementation Plan. King County Department of Community and Human Services (DCHS) is collaborating with City of Seattle Human Services Department, Aging and Disability Services (ADS) on this planning session and the Request for Proposal (RFP) process.

Event Name: Washington Recovery Alliance Orientation-Connecting with the Recovery Community
Event description/details:
Join us for an orientation to the Washington Recovery Alliance and the work of our 9 regional recovery coalitions across the state to change public understanding about substance use recovery and mental health, and advance pro-recovery policies in Washington.
This is a great opportunity to meet other recovery advocates and make new connections. You'll leave this orientation with an understanding of the WRA's work, what advocacy opportunities lie ahead, and how YOU can get involved in making change.

Event Name: North Highline Subarea Plan Community Meeting
Event description/details:
The North Highline Subarea Plan will guide development in North Highline over the next 20 years. It will focus on zoning, long-term land use, and issues like housing, commercial and industrial areas, and community character. The next community meeting will be on Wednesday, Feb. 19, 5:30-6:30 p.m. in the Joe Thomas Room at KCHA-Greenbridge (9800 8th Avenue SW, Seattle). Learn about the plan and share your vision for your neighborhood. Refreshments will be provided. Language interpretation will be provided in Khmer and Vietnamese. Disability accommodations are available on request.

If you can’t attend or have more questions, King County staff members will also be available at the White Center Library (1409 SW 107th Street, Seattle) on Thursday, Feb. 20, 1-5 p.m.
